  "prompt": "Does x = 2x, as the limit of x approaches infinity? Why?",
  "response": "To analyze whether \\( x = 2x \\) as \\( x \\) approaches infinity, let's examine the equation step by step.\n\nGiven the equation:\n\\[ x = 2x \\]\n\nSubtract \\( x \\) from both sides:\n\\[ x - x = 2x - x \\]\n\\[ 0 = x \\]\n\nThis tells us that the equation \\( x = 2x \\) holds true only when \\( x = 0 \\).\n\nNow, let's consider what happens as \\( x \\) approaches infinity. \n\nFor any non-zero value of \\( x \\):\n\\[ x \\neq 2x \\]\n\nThis is because:\n\\[ 2x - x = x \\]\n\\[ x \\neq 0 \\]\n\nAs \\( x \\) approaches infinity, the difference between \\( x \\) and \\( 2x \\) also approaches infinity:\n\\[ 2x - x = x \\rightarrow \\infty \\]\n\nTherefore, the equation \\( x = 2x \\) does not hold as \\( x \\) approaches infinity. The equality \\( x = 2x \\) is only true when \\( x = 0 \\), and it does not become true as \\( x \\) grows larger without bound.\n\nIn conclusion, \\( x \\) does not equal \\( 2x \\) as the limit of \\( x \\) approaches infinity.",
